# heavygee/hapi operator fork

This repo is a **fork** of `tiann/hapi`. Root **`AGENTS.md` is byte-identical to upstream** (intentionally - it's the Codex Cloud RAG-parity surface, see `docs/tooling/pr-review-loop.md` "What `cold-review-clean` means"). Fork-specific guidance lives in `docs/operator/AGENTS.md`, this rule, and the repo-root `CLAUDE.md`.

**Read `docs/operator/AGENTS.md`** - single canonical guide (HAPI baseline + fork intent + upstream PR discipline).

- **New functionality requests:** also read `docs/tooling/new-feature-intake.md`. Orchestrator spawns feature peers with explicit **done vs owned** intake steps (§0 handoff block).
- **Workspace** = `~/coding/hapi` (mirror). **`hapi-driver`** = runtime on `:3006` via `hapi-active` — not the default instruction root.

## Stack-switch tooling: operator-only

**Agents MUST NOT run `hapi-use-worktree`, `hapi-use-driver`, or `hapi-driver-rebuild --activate`.** These swing the live stack on `:3006` and restart hub + runner, which kills every running agent session — including the one running the command. Two outages on 2026-06-10 02:14 and 2026-06-11 14:00 BST were caused by agents doing this to test their own dev worktrees.

**`HAPI_STACK_SWITCH_YES=1` is for operator scripts** (cron, CI, `hapi-watch-activate-driver`) — never for agent tool-calls. The script now refuses with `REFUSE: caller PWD is at or under the target worktree` if you try this from inside your own worktree (commit 2026-06-11). It also refuses if `HAPI_AGENT_CONTEXT=1` is set in the env.

**To get your feature branch onto live `:3006`:**

```yaml
# Operator (or you, with explicit operator approval) edits:
# ~/.config/hapi/driver-manifest.yaml
layers:
  - branch: your/branch-name
```

```bash
hapi-driver-rebuild --build-web --verify    # merges into driver/integration, builds, tests; NO hub touch
# Then ask the operator: "ready for hapi-use-driver?"
```

**Other rules:**

- **Before any `hapi-driver-rebuild` or `hapi-use-worktree`:** run `hapi-driver-status --quiet` (exit 0 idle, 75 busy, 2 stale). Operator-side check; agents must not be running these in the first place. See `docs/tooling/driver-soup.md#coordination-avoid-stack-switch-contention`.

## sudo systemctl on hapi services: blocked at three layers (cross-agent)

`sudo systemctl stop|restart|kill|disable|mask hapi-{hub,runner,runner-watchdog}.service` is **forbidden for agents** and blocked by three layers as of 2026-06-11. The layers are complementary — different agents and call shapes hit different layers — and together cover every realistic invocation path:

1. **systemctl wrapper on `secure_path`** (`/usr/local/sbin/systemctl`, source `scripts/tooling/sudoers/systemctl-wrapper.sh`, installed via `install-systemctl-wrapper.sh`) — this is the **agent-agnostic** layer. sudo's `secure_path` resolves `/usr/local/sbin` first, so any `sudo systemctl ...` call from any agent (Cursor, Claude, Codex, Gemini, cron, ad-hoc shell) hits the wrapper before reaching `/bin/systemctl`. The wrapper parses argv, refuses destructive verbs against hapi-* units with a recovery message, exec's `/bin/systemctl` for everything else. **Catches `sudo bash -c 'systemctl stop ...'` shell-wrap** because bash inherits sudo's PATH which starts with `/usr/local/sbin`.
2. **Sudoers !-deny rule** (`/etc/sudoers.d/hapi-protect`, source `scripts/tooling/sudoers/hapi-protect`) — catches the absolute-path bypass `sudo /bin/systemctl stop ...` that the wrapper does not see. Visible in `sudo -l` so the prohibition is self-documenting. Deny rule has no NOPASSWD so sudo asks for a password, effectively refusing under `-n`.
3. **Cursor preToolUse hook** (`scripts/tooling/hapi-systemctl-guard.sh`) — preempts the call at the agent's Shell tool layer before sudo even fires. Cursor-specific (per-agent hook systems differ), but gives the cleanest recovery message because it returns structured `permission: deny` JSON to the agent. Other agent harnesses can have their own hook ports added later — the wrapper makes those redundant for the systemctl case but they would still give cleaner error UX.

Coverage matrix:

| Call | Wrapper | Sudoers | Cursor hook |
|------|---------|---------|-------------|
| `sudo systemctl stop hapi-hub.service` | BLOCK | BLOCK | BLOCK |
| `sudo bash -c 'systemctl stop hapi-hub.service'` | BLOCK | blind | BLOCK |
| `sudo /bin/systemctl stop hapi-hub.service` | blind | DENY | BLOCK |
| `sudo systemctl status hapi-hub.service` | ALLOW | ALLOW | ALLOW |
| `sudo systemctl start hapi-hub.service` (recovery) | ALLOW | ALLOW | ALLOW |
| `sudo systemctl restart hapi-runner.service` (watchdog) | ALLOW | ALLOW | ALLOW |
| `sudo cp /bin/systemctl /tmp/x; sudo /tmp/x stop hapi-*` | blind | blind | blind (documented kill-criterion) |

Allowed paths:

- `sudo systemctl status hapi-hub.service` — read-only.
- `sudo systemctl start hapi-hub.service` — recovery action when hub is already down.
- `sudo systemctl restart hapi-runner.service` — what `hapi-runner-watchdog.service` needs (one-line whitelist in `/etc/sudoers.d/hapi-watchdog`).

For destructive operations use:

- `hapi-restart-hub` — patient drain, 10min timeout (`--impatient` for hung-hub).
- `hapi-use-worktree <path>` — stack switch with pre-flight schema + auto-revert. Operator-only, see preceding section.

Bypasses (operator-approved, **TTY-gated since 2026-06-13**):

- `HAPI_OPERATOR_SYSTEMCTL_OVERRIDE=1` — only honored when the caller has a controlling terminal (operator at SSH/tmux/local console). Agent tool-call shells have piped stdin and `tty_nr=0`; the env-var-alone bypass is **ignored** in those contexts and the wrapper refuses with `BLOCKED (operator override IGNORED - no controlling tty)`. The check reads `/proc/$PPID/stat` field 7. Cursor preToolUse hooks gate the same env var on `[ -t 0 ]` which is always false for agent-piped invocations. This gate landed on 2026-06-13 because an agent in worktree `mermaid-feedback` ended up running `HAPI_OPERATOR_SYSTEMCTL_OVERRIDE=1 sudo -E systemctl stop hapi-hub.service`, which cascade-killed the runner and 10 sessions. The agent had the supported path (`HAPI_IMPATIENT=1 hapi-restart-hub`) one decision step away. **Read the gate as a tooling fix, not a fence**: the previous documentation listed the override env var as the operator emergency bypass without enough friction against using it from an agent shell, so an agent under operator pressure to "just fix it" reached for the bypass instead of the wrapper. The wrapper's refusal message now opens with a "did you mean..." menu pointing at `hapi-restart-hub`, `HAPI_IMPATIENT=1 hapi-restart-hub`, runner-only restart, and the hub journal so the next agent in the same spot has the supported path one read away.
- `HAPI_USE_WORKTREE_FROM_INSIDE=1` — same TTY gate. Without a controlling terminal the wrapper guard fires anyway.
- `HAPI_USE_WORKTREE_FROM_AGENT=1` — same TTY gate. The "operator-driven agent that has cause" use case effectively requires the operator to drive from a real terminal; agent-shell-only invocation no longer bypasses.
- `HAPI_OPERATOR_PRODUCT_EDIT_OVERRIDE=1` — Cursor preToolUse hook gates this on `[ -t 0 ]`; agent tool-call hooks always have piped stdin so the bypass is effectively removed for agent-driven invocations.
- File-level rollback when the gate fires for a legitimate operator who can't get a real terminal: `sudo mv /usr/local/sbin/systemctl{,.disabled}`, do the thing, restore. Or roll back the wrapper to the prior binary at `/usr/local/sbin/systemctl.prev` (kept by the installer for one rotation).
- Edit `/etc/sudoers.d/hapi-protect` to remove specific entries — bypasses sudoers. Audit trail.

See `docs/tooling/driver-soup.md#patient-restarts-dont-yank-live-agents` for the wrapper rationale.
- Upstream PR branches: from `upstream/main` only; never include `docs/operator/`, `docs/plans/`, or `CLAUDE.md` in the PR diff (root `AGENTS.md` IS upstream-compatible and may appear in diffs only if a branch updates project-overview content with upstream's blessing).
